[This is the same general area as the previous report -- 16 Jul 2018 Anthrax - France: (MO,HA) bovine, OIE 20180716.5908970 -- and the OIE website contains a map. The Hautes-Alpes outbreaks are in south east France close to the border with Italy. Hautes-Alpes is one of the original 83 departments created during the French Revolution on 4 Mar 1790. It consists of the south east of the former province of Dauphin and the north of Provence. (See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hautes-Alpes)

For Ancelle, go to http://www.fallingrain.com/world/FR/B8/Ancelle.html. For Theus, go to http://www.fallingrain.com/world/FR/B8/Theus.html. These 2 communes are a distance apart. Montgardin is south east of Ancelle, (http://www.fallingrain.com/world/FR/B8/Montgardin.html). Interestingly Chorges is immediately downstream of Montgardin, (http://www.fallingrain.com/world/FR/B8/Chorges.html). La Batie-Neuve has not made its way to Fallingrain yet but La Batie-Vieille (presumably related, "Old Batie") is close to Montgardin, (http://www.fallingrain.com/world/FR/B8/La_BatieVieille.html).

The advice to not pick berries or mushrooms is beyond me. Certainly don't pick mushrooms near a carcass nor berries just in case they are contaminated. But anything more than 5 metres [about 16 feet] away should be safe.

The previous OIE report was for Montgardin, but it is now revealed to have been recently diagnosed in La Batie-Neuve and Chorges, and latterly in Ancelle and Theus, for a total of 10 outbreaks in the 5 communes. Where the affected communes are adjoining one might suspect that tabanid biting flies are contributing to the problem. But for distant communes an alternative cause will have to be found. Maybe just a repeat of what initiated the index outbreak, a possible cattle grave disturbance. - Mod.MHJ

